<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ871021-0089 </DOCNO><HL> Sears Posts RiseIn Profit of 25%For 3rd Quarter---By Jean Marie BrownStaff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DD> 10/21/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> SEARNINGS (ERN)RETAILING (RET) </IN><DATELINE> CHICAGO  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sears, Roebuck andamp; Co. posted a 25% rise in third-quarter earnings, reflecting a tax benefit, the sale of a shopping center and higher earnings from its Allstate Insurance Group.    The retailing and financial services concern earned a record $409 million, or $1.08 a share, compared with $328.1 million, or 88 cents a share, in the year-earlier period. Revenue rose 9% to $12.19 billion from $11.17 billion a year earlier.    The results from Sears's units were mixed. While earnings from Allstate and the Coldwell Banker Real Estate Group were stronger, results were flat at its merchandise group. The Dean Witter Financial Services Group generated a smaller loss compared with the year-earlier quarter.    Allstate's earnings rose 20% to $240.5 million from $200.9 million during the 1986 third quarter. Among other things, the unit cited a net gain of $18.3 million related to a tax benefit. Allstate's revenue rose 21% to $3.97 billion from $3.29 billion.    Coldwell Banker earnings jumped to $47.8 million from $7.8 million for the 1986 quarter, primarily because the unit sold a shopping center. Revenue for the real estate unit totaled $342.8 million, rising 5.6% from $324.5 million a year earlier.    Earnings at Sears's biggest unit, the merchandising group, totaled $170.4 million compared with $170.0 million a year earlier. Revenue rose 4% to $6.96 billion from $6.68 billion.    The Dean Witter unit trimmed its third-quarter loss to $4.2 million from the $8 million loss a year earlier. Dean Witter revenue rose 22% to $1.02 billion from $837.3 million a year earlier.    Losses for Discover Card widened to $29.4 million from $28.4 million.    For the nine months, Sears earnings rose 35% to $1.09 billion, or $2.86 a share, from $808.3 million, or $2.17 a share, a year earlier. Revenue increased 9.8% to $34.39 billion from $31.31 billion. </TEXT></DOC>